{{Infobox Buddhist temple | name = Nikko-in | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = [[File:Tajimamyoken08.JPG|270px]] | location = 450 Ishihara, Yoka-chō, Yabu-shi, Hyōgo, Japan | latitude_deg = 35 | latitude_min = 24 | latitude_sec = 40 | longitude_deg= 134 | longitude_min = 42 | longitude_sec = 0 | map = {{location map|Japan Hyōgo|lat_deg=35|lat_min=24|lat_sec=40|lon_deg=134|lon_min=42|lon_sec=0|label=Nikko-in|mark=Japanese Map symbol (Temple).svg|marksize=11|position=center|width=200|float=center}} | mountain = Myoken-san | denomination = [[Koyasan Shingon-shu]] | principal = [[Myoken Bosatsu|Myoken Daibosatsu]] | founded = Reign of Emperor Bidatsu | founder = Nikko Keiju | cultural = | pilgrimage = [[Kinki Rakuju Kannon Pilgrimage]] No. 5 }} '''Nikko-in''' (日光院) is a [[Koyasan Shingon-shu]] temple located in {{ill|Yabu|ja|養父市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yabu|qq=}}, {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|ja|兵庫県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hyōgo Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. It is part of the Myoken-san complex and venerates [[Myoken Bosatsu]] (Myoken Daibosatsu) as its principal image. It is one of the "Three Great Myoken" temples of Japan.
== History == According to temple tradition, Nikko-in was founded during the reign of [[Emperor Bidatsu]] (6th century CE) by the monk Nikko Keiju, who established a hermitage at the site.
In [[1485]] (17th year of the [[Bunmei era]]), the temple received a land grant from {{ill|Yamana Masatoyo|ja|山名政豊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamana Masatoyo|qq=}}, demonstrating its historical significance.<ref>Yamana Masatoyo’s Myoken Shrine Land Grant (document held by Nikko-in) {{harv|Hyōgo Prefectural Archaeological Museum|2010|p=38}}.</ref>
