{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q11504904]] Wikidata name: Nikkō-in [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 08:31, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} {{Infobox Buddhist temple | name = Nikko-in | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = File:Tajimamyoken08.JPG | location = 450 Ishihara, Yoka-chō, Yabu-shi, Hyōgo, Japan | latitude_deg = 35 | latitude_min = 24 | latitude_sec = 40 | longitude_deg= 134 | longitude_min = 42 | longitude_sec = 0 | map = {{location map|Japan Hyōgo|lat_deg=35|lat_min=24|lat_sec=40|lon_deg=134|lon_min=42|lon_sec=0|label=Nikko-in|mark=Japanese Map symbol (Temple).svg|marksize=11|position=center|width=200|float=center}} | mountain = Myoken-san | denomination = [[:en:Koyasan Shingon-shu|Koyasan Shingon-shu]] | principal = [[:en:Myōken|Myoken Daibosatsu]] | founded = Reign of Emperor Bidatsu | founder = Nikko Keiju | cultural = | pilgrimage = [[Kinki Rakuju Kannon Pilgrimage]] No. 5 | prefecture= {{ill|Yabu|qid=Q869014}} | coordinates= {{Coord|35.411111|N|134.7|E|region:JP_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | deity= {{ill|Myōken|qid=Q10960623}} }} '''Nikko-in''' (日光院) is a [[:en:Koyasan Shingon-shu|Koyasan Shingon-shu]] temple located in [[:en:Yabu, Hyōgo|Yabu]], [[:en:Hyōgo Prefecture|Hyōgo Prefecture]], Japan. It is part of the Myoken-san complex and venerates [[:en:Myōken|Myōken]] (Myoken Daibosatsu) as its principal image. It is one of the "Three Great Myoken" temples of Japan.
== History == According to temple tradition, Nikko-in was founded during the reign of [[Emperor Bidatsu]] (6th century CE) by the monk Nikko Keiju, who established a hermitage at the site.
In [[:en:1485|1485]] (17th year of the [[Bunmei era]]), the temple received a land grant from {{ill|Yamana Masatoyo|ja|山名政豊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamana Masatoyo|qq=|1=Masatoyo Yamana|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11467585}}, demonstrating its historical significance.<ref>Yamana Masatoyo’s Myoken Shrine Land Grant (document held by Nikko-in) {{harv|Hyōgo Prefectural Archaeological Museum|2010|p=38}}.</ref>
== Related sites == * [[Myoken-san (Yabu and Kami)|Myoken-san]] * [[Nagusa Shrine]] * [[Soma Myoken]] (Fukushima Prefecture) * [[Yatsushiro Shrine|Yatsushiro Myoken]] (Kumamoto Prefecture)
== References == {{reflist}} *{{Cite book|和書|author=Hyōgo Prefectural Archaeological Museum|title=The Sengoku Period Guardians: Yamana Clan Castles and Battles|date=2010|ref=harv}}
